7–Zesnulý","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1431–1456":"1431–1456","1430–1458":"1430–1458","1458":"1458","1447":"1447","1524":"1524","1456":"1456","1431":"1431","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"okolo 1450","about 1472":"okolo 1472","Penn, Staffordshire, England":"Penn, Staffordshire, Anglie","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1450–":"omkring 1450–Afdød","1428–1524":"1428–1524","1450–Female":"1450–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1447–Male":"1447–Afdød","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1431–1456":"1431–1456","1430–1458":"1430–1458","1458":"1458","1447":"1447","1524":"1524","1456":"1456","1431":"1431","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"omkring 1450","about 1472":"omkring 1472","Penn, Staffordshire, England":"Penn, Staffordshire, England","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1450–":"circa 1450–Overleden","1428–1524":"1428–1524","1450–Female":"1450–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1447–Male":"1447–Overleden","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1431–1456":"1431–1456","1430–1458":"1430–1458","1458":"1458","1447":"1447","1524":"1524","1456":"1456","1431":"1431","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"circa 1450","about 1472":"circa 1472","Penn, Staffordshire, England":"Penn, Staffordshire, England","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"about 1450–":"about 1450–Deceased","1428–1524":"1428–1524","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1447–Male":"1447–Deceased","1485–1524":"1485–1524","1431–1456":"1431–1456","1430–1458":"1430–1458","1458":"1458","1447":"1447","1524":"1524","1456":"1456","1431":"1431","1485":"1485","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"about 1450","about 1472":"about 1472","Penn, Staffordshire, England":"Penn, Staffordshire, England","Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stanley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Stanley, including those in Yorkshire, Staffordshire, Derbyshire, Durham, Gloucestershire, and Wiltshire, named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. This English name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century where it was Gaelicized as <b>de Stainléigh</b>.","English: possibly also a variant of <b>Stoneley</b>, a habitational name from Stoneley Green in Burland (Cheshire), Stoneleigh (Warwickshire), or Stonely in Kimbolton (Huntingdonshire), all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of any of various like-sounding names in other languages, for example Polish   Stanislawski  , Greek   Anastasiou  , and Serbian <b>Stojadinov</b> (patronymic from the personal name <i>Stojadin</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Stanislawski","meanings":["Polish (<b>Stanisławski</b>): habitational name for someone from any of various places called Stanisław, Stanisławów, or Stanisławice, named with the personal name <i>Stanisław</i> (see   Stanislav  )."]},{"name":"Standley","meanings":["English: variant of   Stanley  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Stanley was born about 1450, in Flintshire, Wales, her father, Piers Stanley I, was 20 and her mother, Margaret Heleigh, was 21. She married James Grosvenor about 1472, in Eaton, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et"